notable_fact: Known as the "City in the Country" and for its agriculture and annual Abbotsford International Airshow.
Named after HMS Ajax, a Royal Navy cruiser. Developed around a shell manufacturing plant during WWII.
Located north of Toronto. Known for its preserved historic downtown.
Located on Kempenfelt Bay on Lake Simcoe. Popular recreational destination.
Located on the Bay of Quinte. Gateway to Prince Edward County wine region.
Located north of Montreal. One of Quebec's fastest-growing municipalities.
Located north of Montreal. Former site of a GM automobile assembly plant.
One of the oldest municipalities in Quebec. Known for its historic old village.
One of Canada's fastest-growing cities with a large South Asian population.
Second-largest city in Manitoba. Known as the "Wheat City".
Known as the "Telephone City" as the home of Alexander Graham Bell when he invented the telephone.
Located on Montreal's South Shore. Known for its multicultural population.
Located at the western end of Lake Ontario. Known for the Royal Botanical Gardens.
Home to Simon Fraser University and Metropolis at Metrotown, BC's largest shopping mall.
Located in the Greater Toronto Area. Known for its scenic hills and conservation areas.
Known for the Calgary Stampede and its proximity to the Rocky Mountains.
Formed by the amalgamation of Galt, Preston, and Hespeler. Known for its historic architecture.
Regional municipality on Cape Breton Island. Known for its scenic Cabot Trail.
Capital of Prince Edward Island. Known as the "Birthplace of Confederation".
Formed by the amalgamation of 23 separate communities. Known for its agricultural industry.
Agricultural community in the Fraser Valley. Name derived from the Ts'elxwéyeqw First Nation.
Located southwest of Montreal. Site of the Battle of Châteauguay during the War of 1812.
Easternmost municipality in the Greater Toronto Area. Home to the Darlington Nuclear Generating Station.
Part of Metro Vancouver. Name derived from the indigenous Kwikwetlem First Nation.
Located along the St. Lawrence River. Former textile manufacturing center.
Located south of Vancouver at the mouth of the Fraser River. Known for its agricultural lands.
Located on the Saint-François River. Known for its annual Festival mondial de folklore.
Capital of Alberta. Known for West Edmonton Mall, once the largest mall in the world.
Capital of New Brunswick. Known for its cultural institutions and historic buildings.
Forms the National Capital Region with Ottawa. Home to the Canadian Museum of History.
Located east of Montreal. Known for its zoo and annual hot air balloon festival.
Hub of the Peace River Country. Center for oil and gas exploration in northwestern Alberta.
Known for its limestone architecture and the University of Guelph.
Rural municipality along the Grand River and Lake Erie shore. Known for its agricultural lands.
Capital of Nova Scotia and major economic center for Atlantic Canada.
Major industrial center often called "Steel City" for its steel manufacturing history.
Capital of Nunavut. Name means "place of many fish" in Inuktitut.
Located at the confluence of the North and South Thompson Rivers. Name means "meeting of the waters".
City formed by the amalgamation of Victoria County. Known for its many lakes and rivers.
Located in the Okanagan Valley. Known for its wineries and fruit orchards.
Part of the Tri-Cities area with Cambridge and Waterloo. Known for its annual Oktoberfest.
Known as the "Birthplace of BC" and for its agricultural lands and wineries.
Located on Île Jésus north of Montreal. Quebec's third-largest city.
Third-largest city in Alberta. Known for its coulees and high-level bridge.
Known as the "Forest City" and home to Western University.
Located on the south shore of the St. Lawrence River opposite Montreal.
Located opposite Quebec City on the south shore of the St. Lawrence River.
Located in the northeastern section of Greater Vancouver. Known for its natural scenery.
Known as Canada's high-tech capital with many international company headquarters.
Located north of Montreal. Rapidly growing suburban community.
Known as "The Gas City" due to its large natural gas fields. Has one of the lowest utility rates in Canada.
One of the fastest-growing municipalities in Canada. Located at the edge of the Niagara Escarpment.
Created to accommodate Montreal's international airport. Now primarily agricultural.
Located in the Fraser Valley. Known for its forestry heritage and Stave Lake.
Located in the Greater Toronto Area. Home to Toronto Pearson International Airport.
Largest city in New Brunswick. Known as the "Hub of the Maritimes".
Second-largest city in Canada and largest in Quebec. Known for its cultural diversity and festivals.
Known as the "Harbour City" and for the sweet Nanaimo bar dessert.
Former capital of British Columbia. Known as the "Royal City".
Located north of Toronto. Known for its historic downtown.
Famous for the Niagara Falls waterfalls. Major tourist destination.
Known as Ontario's Garden. Major agricultural producer, especially of tobacco.
Located at the foot of the North Shore Mountains. Gateway to popular ski resorts.
Former city now part of Toronto. Home to the Ontario Science Centre.
Affluent lakeside town known for its harbors, parks, and upscale shopping districts.
Known as the "Automotive Capital of Canada" due to GM manufacturing presence.
Capital city of Canada. Home to Parliament Hill and numerous national museums.
Known as the gateway to the Kawarthas, a popular cottage country destination.
Located east of Toronto. Home to the Pickering Nuclear Generating Station.
Largest city in northern British Columbia. Known as BC's "Northern Capital".
Provincial capital of Quebec. Only fortified city in North America north of Mexico.
Formed by the amalgamation of Trenton, Sidney, Murray and Frankford. Home to CFB Trenton.
Located midway between Edmonton and Calgary. Named after the river that flows through it.
Capital of Saskatchewan. Home to the RCMP training academy.
Located northeast of Montreal. One of Quebec's oldest European settlements.
Island city with a large Asian population. Home to Vancouver International Airport.
Known for its cultural diversity and as a technology hub in the Greater Toronto Area.
Maritime city on the south shore of the St. Lawrence River. Important regional center.
Mining and smelting center in western Quebec. Known for its annual music festival.
Largest municipality in Greater Victoria. Name comes from the Saanich First Nation.
Oldest incorporated city in Canada. Known for the Reversing Falls.
Located on the Richelieu River. Home to a major military college.
Located in the Laurentians region. Former industrial center now focused on tourism.
Located where Lake Huron flows into the St. Clair River. Known for its petrochemical industry.
Largest city in Saskatchewan. Known as the "City of Bridges".
Located on St. Marys River between Lakes Superior and Huron. One of Canada's oldest settlements.
Former city now part of Toronto. Known for the Scarborough Bluffs and multicultural communities.
Cultural and economic center of the Eastern Townships region of Quebec.
Second-largest city in the Edmonton Metropolitan Region. Consistently ranked among Canada's best places to live.
Largest city in the Niagara Region. Known as "The Garden City".
Capital of Newfoundland and Labrador. Oldest city in North America.
Known as the "Railway City" for its railway heritage. Home to the Jumbo the Elephant monument.
Fast-growing community northeast of Toronto. Blend of urban and rural areas.
Specialized municipality that includes the urban service area of Sherwood Park.
Second-largest city in British Columbia. Known for its parks and rapid growth.
One of Montreal's largest suburbs. Known for its historic old village.
Formed by the merger of Fort William and Port Arthur. Gateway to Northwestern Ontario.
Major mining center in northeastern Ontario. Birthplace of singer Shania Twain.
Largest city in Canada and provincial capital of Ontario. Home to the CN Tower.
Second-oldest city in Quebec. Located at the confluence of the Saint-Maurice and St. Lawrence Rivers.
